    <segment id="1" parent="14" relname="span">
P37, this is a good synopsis of what Raskin states as intuitiveness being equal to 
familiarity.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="15" relname="volitional-cause"> We learn things,</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="16" relname="span"> they become more familiar,</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="10" relname="span"> therefore they become intuitive.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="4" relname="background">

Some HCI-ers like Raskin and others have asked about the intuitiveness of the desktop.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="13" relname="span"> 
How intuitive is it?</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="9" relname="antithesis"> Many workers do not work in an office environment,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="11" relname="span"> yet the classic 
desktop interface was designed to support that metaphor.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="11" relname="elaboration"> Many people are not familiar 
with folders, files, and directories.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="17" relname="span"> The metaphor may not extend as well as we think.</segment>
